text.text:
Well built with good intent but, Poorly maintained.
Badly managed.
That's the summary.
The community hall roof has been leaking for many years now.
The drains clog up regularly, making it impossible to breathe in the building due to the stench. Specially if you arrive for the morning prayers. Because the stench has been accumulating all night
The community hall has chairs and folding desks and carpets stored in unsafe way.
Again for many years now.
Wireless mic loses signals regularly during sermon and prayers, making it be very difficult to hear what's being said from the podium.
The car park in front of the building and the walkway from the rear car park are in need to a jet wash. The moss , mould and dirt deposit are so bad that paving blocks are barely visible. Also gets slippery and unsafe due to that, when it's raining.
The rear car park gate has no securing point. There's a heap of cinder blocks, but that's hardly the right solution. When the gate is open, it's just swinging, and someday it will hit a passing car.
I understand it's a charitable organization, and management are unpaid volunteers, spending own time for the organization. Kudos to them for what they achieved and are doing.
But that doesn't mean that the above mentioned problems should be ignored for as many years as they have been.

text.text:
Bradford Central Mosque, located in Bradford, is one of the largest in the UK. It serves as a significant religious and cultural center for the local Muslim community.

The building and its architecture is beautiful Grey tonned with golden dome and minaret.
There is a huge parking around the mosque in yard style American format. I offered juma prayer here it was a wonderful experience. The place of ablution is well maintened with ample amount of sitting spaces.

The hall is spacious with option of offering prayer on the second floor upstairs. Equipped with heating chairs for people with special needs. The main entrance is well maintained with huge slots for shoe keeping. There is a funeral services space outside the mosque.

Overall, I really loved offering prayers here.
May God bless us

text.text:
Assalamualaikum Brother,

my name is Maulana... I am muslim from Indonesia. Today I was from Shah Jalal Mosque for Praying Maghrib with my wife (Dian) and my Oman friend Ahmed. We were actually very tired because We just came from Wyemouth city (Long Journey) for field trip work, and decided to have Shalat in the mosque before heading back.

The problem is, my wife was offended by one of your brother (wearing white robe) with loud voice (not polite at all), saying that she could not wait in the near entrance door. If the brother said with polite words, would be okay, but he said with the bad gesture, shouting to her, and throwing out of her, while my wife was just doing nothing.

I was not with her, because I was still doing shalat with brothers. She already finished pray from upstair, and waiting for us. But there was no waiting space for sisters downstair.

Please don't do this again to any sister. I am muslim and sometimes pray in Victoria Central Mosque, Mc Dougall and some places. I do find all brothers here is very helpful and kind to Indonesia Muslim. I don't know how to say this to you, But I don't think this is right. My wife was terified about this condition.

Sorry If this is a long story for today. Thank you, and I am sorry to tell you this.

With best regards,
Maulana

text.text: I was travelling and my flight was on Friday at 8 PM. I checked out from my Airbnb at 10 AM as per their rules and Allah guided me to his house (Masjid Al Hidayah) through a random google maps search and I went straight to Masjid Al Hidayah for Jumuah Prayer, I was hungry, Cold and had my luggage with me, the masjid was yet to open as I arrived early (10:35 AM) and I was standing in Masjid Parking Lot. One of the worshipper who came early saw me standing with my luggage in freezing weather and he redirected me to the kitchen managed by a kind Gujrati gentlemen, The Kitchen Manager (May Allah bless him abundantly) he had not only provided me shelter inside the kitchen till the masjid opened but he was kind enough to offer me a tasty hot meal, It was a pure blessing in a freezing weather. I'm thankful to Allah SWT for this blessings. I was Fed, I got Shelter for 3 hours, Offered Jumuah Prayer and happily left for the Airport. Thank you to the Gujrati Kitchen Manager/ Head Chef at Masjid Al Hidayah. I will be forever grateful for your gesture. Im sorry I forgot your name.

Was banned from attending this mosque during the month of Ramadan. the reason behind it was parking my car 'incorrectly' when it caused no obstruction or inconvenience to any other visitor.

The committee had padlocked the gates and trapped us inside and was forcing us to donate money to the masjid so we could leave and they were calling it a 'donation' however you cannot force someone to 'donate'. after approx. 30 mins of trying to leave, the committee then reluctantly opened the gates so we could leave. bearing in mind this is in Ramadan and we had just read Asr as we were travelling through Leeds. they delayed us so much we we almost missed our Iftar. the staff/ committee is outrageous and extremely money hungry so if you decide to visit this mosque, please ensure you are aware of your surroundings at all times as they will do anything to take money off you. once they had realised we will not be giving any money, they allowed us to leave and then proceeded to ban us from future visits to this masjid. as this is the house of Allah, i will openly head into this mosque in the future whenever i am passing through Leeds again and i need to pray :)
